tramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>BBS/E/J/000CA452</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Phytoplasmas are insect-transmitted pathogens of plants that cause disease in important crops. Aster Yellows phytoplasma strain Witches? Broom (AY-WB) induces symptoms that indicate developmental processes are perturbed in infected plants, including the growth of leaf-like flowers (phyllody) and the proliferation of stems (witches? broom phenotype). We hypothesize that AY-WB secretes effector proteins that alter plant development and down-regulate host defense mechanisms. The objectives of this proposal are: i) determine how the effector genes are regulated; and ii) functionally characterize a subset of putative effectors to determine whether these proteins modulate plant development. To realize these objectives, we propose the following experimental approaches. We will map promoters associated with genes encoding candidate effectors that are highly expressed in an insect or a plant host. Promoter sequences and upstream regions will be examined to identify regulatory elements that are associated with a host-specific expression, providing insight into the regulation of phytoplasma gene expression, and allowing the development of in silico promoter prediction methodologies. Furthermore, we will select a subset of AY-WB candidate effectors for functional characterization. The effector genes will be expressed in Arabidopsis, and the phenotype of the transgenic plants will be assessed to identify alterations in development. As phytoplasmas are restricted to the phloem of infected hosts, we will employ immunocytology to localize the effector proteins in infected plant tissues to assess whether the secreted phytoplasma proteins unload from the phloem and whether AY-WB encodes (additional) proteins that facilitate effector unloading into distal tissues. Finally, we will screen the putative effectors to probe for protein-protein interactions against an Arabidopsis cDNA library as a means of identifying (plant) host proteins that are targeted by the bacterial effectors.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-05-22</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-05-23</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_PROJECTED</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71122</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput><gtr:description>Generated a video explaining how plants become zombies and posted this on YouTube. The videos features researchers explaining the research and doing experiments, and plants with disease symptoms and insect pests.</gtr:description><gtr:id>A776CBB2-BD98-4D4C-B480-7A4F0829D005</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The video was released as part of a press release for the MacLean et al., 2014. PLoS Biol publication. It received attention from journalists worldwide who covered the findings in newspapers, local journals and prestigious news letters to engage the general public.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58b84c68a53f13.28868855</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>Produced a video</gtr:title><gtr:type>Film/Video/Animation</gtr:type><gtr:url>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QGTESwEeqsM&amp;feature=youtu.be</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2014</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutput></gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>450000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>France, French Republic</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>USD</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>Ecuador</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>es_EC</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Human Frontier Science Program (HFSP) Research Grant</gtr:description><gtr:end>2019-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Human Frontier Science Program (HFSP)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>RGP0024/2015</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>C6E8B46C-E354-4F05-9499-28831A5A02C9</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58b7423947ecc9.33680918</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2015-08-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Phytoplasmas are insect-transmitted plant pathogens that infect a range of globally important agricultural crops. Unlike many phytopathogens which must penetrate plant cell walls to gain access to the cytoplasm, phytoplasmas are injected directly into the cytoplasm of phloem sieve cells of a plant via the feeding activity of an insect vector.

In addition to symptoms of general decline and plant death, phytoplasmas such as AY-WB induce a range of symptoms that are reflective of an abnormal development of plant tissues, including the formation of witches' broom (a dense mass of shoots originating from a single point), phyllody (retrograde metamorphosis of floral organs into leaves), virescence (green pigmentation of tissues such as flowers) and bolting (growth of elongated stalks). These observations are consistent with a hypothesis that phytoplasmas modulate the growth and development of plants, possibly to enhance the attractiveness of the plant towards egg-laying insects; these alterations in morphology may create protective niches and prolong a vegetative growth phase that is more favourable for egg laying.

Once infected by phytoplasmas, plants cannot be cured. Control strategies primarily entail the sustained application of environmentally harmful pesticides as a means of reducing the vector populations. Economically, phytoplasmas cause significant problems in global crop production, and are responsible for such devastating diseases as the coconut lethal yellowing diseases (CLYD) of Africa and the Caribbean that lead to the impoverishment of local farmers. According to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, CLYD has resulted in the loss of coconut plantations in Tanzania, and has impoverished rural communities in Ghana that depend upon coconuts as a primary food source. The productivity of European crops has also been adversely affected by phytoplasmas, with grape vineyards and apple orchards suffering significant economic losses. Despite the economic importance of these organisms, little is known about how phytoplasmas regulate interaction with respective hosts. This project has helped to increase current knowledge of phytoplasma regulatory mechanisms.

This project has impacted society at several levels: (A) Interactions among science disciplines; (B) Training of young scientists; (C) Communication of science to (inter)national science communities; and (D) Engagement with the general public.

(A) Interactions among science disciplines

This research is interdisciplinary, as it unified the study of organisms spanning three Kingdoms (namely Prokaryota, Animalia, and Plantae) and thus incorporated microbiology, entomology, and plant biology. This project also adopted a multidisciplinary approach, with a primary focus upon molecular biology and expression profiling, coupled with bioinformatics, biochemistry, bioassays, and microscopy. Phytoplasma effectors are unique in that they interfere with fundamental developmental pathways of a plant, whereas classical effectors secreted by other phytopathogens typically target plant defence pathways. In addition, our work with SAP11 and SAP54 demonstrated that these effectors interfere with plant defences against insects, thus phytoplasma virulence proteins also affect a third organism in the interaction, the insect vector.

(B) Training of young scientists

This project help develop a postdoctoral researcher for 2 years.

The post doc was a member of the supervisory team of a DTP PhD student.

The post doc co-supervised visiting (inter)national MSc and PhD students. 

(C) Communication of science to (inter)national science communities

The post doc was an invited speaker in the symposium &amp;quot;Interconnected lifecycles: multitrophic interactions between plants, pathogens and insects,&amp;quot; American Phytopathological Society (APS), 2014 Annual American Phytopathological Society - Canadian Phytopathological Society Joint Meeting, Minneapolis, USA, 9-13 August 2014.

Our paper MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was co-authored with colleagues (Richard Immink and Gerco Angenent) at Wageningen University and Research Centre, Wageningen, The Netherlands.

MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was the most viewed article of PLoS Biology April issue (10,417 views on 4 May 2014)

Contributed a featured image for PLoS Biology April 2014 issue.

MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was featured in Research Highlights: 'How bacteria turn plants into zombies' Nature 50: 152 (10 April 2014).

MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was rated 'Exceptional' and 'Very Good' and listed in the Hidden Jewels rankings of Faculty of 1000.

MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was featured in Nature Microbiology Reviews.

The post doc was an invited speaker at the JIC Annual Science Meeting as postdoc representative from Department of Cellular and Developmental Biology, Oct 2013 and an invited speaker at the Bacterial Effector session of the &amp;quot;Effectome&amp;quot; meeting, Auberge du Cedre, Lauret, France, Sept 2013.

Our work was described in a comprehensive review in the Annual Review of Phytopathology (Sugio et al., 2011. Vol. 49: 175-195). 

