MacLean et al. (2014). PLoS Biol. 12: e1001835 was highlighted in on-line national media of China (China today), Japan, Russia, USA, Vietnam, Indonesia, Greece, Italy, Spain, France, Germany, The Netherlands (Scientias; Nieuws.nl; Quest; Acksmedia) and UK (Daily Mail; EDP24).</gtr:description><gtr:id>CC192AAC-FB85-4F2A-A291-9756913B6701</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54621098a8e941.61419509</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Education,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The main objective of this proposal was to functionally characterize six phytoplasma effectors to determine whether these proteins modulate plant development and affect plant susceptibility and attractiveness to phytoplasma insect vector. 

Expression analyses of about 50 phytoplasma candidate effector genes during phytoplasma infections of plant hosts and insect vectors showed that about a third are upregulated in the insect vector and two third in the plant hosts. Thus, the effectors are differentially regulated reflecting their activities in the insect vectors or plant hosts. 

We previous found that SAP11 induces leaf crinkling and stem proliferation in A. thaliana (BBS_E_J_000CA317), SAP54 induces the formation of leaf-like flowers and SAP05 the formation of aerial rosettes in these plants (BB/G001928/1). In this project we further described the leaf-like flower phenotypes of SAP54 transgenic plants. We also identified two additional phytoplasma effectors that induce severe stunting in these plants. 

We also found that four phytoplasma effectors change plant susceptibility to insect vectors. SAP54 promotes insect vector attraction and egg laying on A. thaliana plants, whereas two other phytoplasma effectors reduce A. thaliana non-host resistance to the maize-specialist leafhopper Dalbulus maidis; these insects survive longer and lay eggs on A. thaliana plants. Finally, one effector reduces leafhopper survival and reproduction. 

We further investigated how SAP54 interferes with flower development in plants. This work demonstrated that SAP54 interacts with MADS-box transcription factors (MTFs), which perform key roles in a variety of plant developmental processes, including the regulation of the transition from the vegetative to reproductive phase and the formation of flower structures. SAP54 degrades MTFs. SAP54 does this by interacting with members of the RAD23 family, which shuttle SAP54-MTF complexes to the plant 'garbage bin'. In the absence of the RAD23 members, plants produce normal flowers when infected with phytoplasmas. RAD23 (and the degradation of MTFs by SAP54) is also required for the attraction of leafhoppers to phytoplasma-infected plants.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We were the first to show the mechanisms by which virulence proteins (effectors) of microbial pathogens affect plant flower development and that this impacts plant resistance to insect pests. This connection between plant development and defense is important, because breeding efforts targeted to promote yields of crops may potentially be counter productive if they lead to decreased plant resistance to pathogens and pests. We (and others) will explore this further.

We are exploring knowledge generated in this project for engineering SAP54 to target the degradation of specific MTFs leading to desirable phenotypes in plants (funded by BBS/E/J/000C0623). When successful, this line of research will be licensed and becomes attractive for funding by industry.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>6BEE9FF4-D23D-47B1-B655-28A103812686</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54621127e83454.28462001</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Chemicals,Education,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.jic.ac.uk/staff/saskia-hogenhout/Phytoplasma/index.html</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3B5D9BED-D75F-41DF-AEF9-F2A844B7CBCF</gtr:id><gtr:title>Diverse targets of phytoplasma effectors: from plant development to defense against insects.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Annual review of phytopathology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e610428455c7e3d119e6967f3044dce9"><gtr:id>e610428455c7e3d119e6967f3044dce9</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sugio A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0066-4286</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>54465e19982092.91864232</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>89196E2E-5988-45A1-BF00-B6E7F2B7B2D9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Phloem - Molecular Cell Biology, Systemic Communication, Biotic Interactions</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1889afabce7916f991463c5ea00f85ec"><gtr:id>1889afabce7916f991463c5ea00f85ec</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>MacLean A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780470958605</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>5446655f47f3c6.21502038</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E2AC24AB-9538-4C50-8A17-38AD0F667818</gtr:id><gtr:title>Phytoplasma effector SAP54 hijacks plant reproduction by degrading MADS-box proteins and promotes insect colonization in a RAD23-dependent manner.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>PLoS biology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/3145fab20d1256f266e0e88c046f83f6"><gtr:id>3145fab20d1256f266e0e88c046f83f6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>MacLean AM</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1544-9173</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>54465e181c67c4.46446414</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A5FD49D4-8BC9-4012-AA78-EA1EF3BCB257</gtr:id><gtr:title>Phytoplasma effector SAP54 induces indeterminate leaf-like flower development in Arabidopsis plants.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Plant physiology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/3145fab20d1256f266e0e88c046f83f6"><gtr:id>3145fab20d1256f266e0e88c046f83f6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>MacLean AM</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0032-0889</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>54465e1b21af48.95141913</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">BBS/E/J/000CA452</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>D05BC2E0-0345-4A3F-8C3F-775BC42A0819</gtr:id><gtr:text>Unclassified</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>